## 5) Useful filters

You can combine these as query params:

- `limit=5000`
- `order=desc`
- `from_ms=1743465600000`
- `to_ms=1743552000000`
- `symbol=ADAUSDT.P`
- `tf=15`
- `stream_id=B1M,B2M_AP,B3M_PIVOTS`
- `run_id=RUN|...`
- `request_id=...`
- `uid=...`
- `columns=uid,symbol,tf,t_close_ms,close,stream_id`
- `include_payload=1`

Examples:

### Latest bars for one symbol

```text
https://YOUR_APP_URL/export/bars.csv?secret=YOUR_SECRET&symbol=ADAUSDT.P&limit=5000
```

### Only B1M bars in a time window

```text
https://YOUR_APP_URL/export/bars.csv?secret=YOUR_SECRET&stream_id=B1M&from_ms=1743465600000&to_ms=1743552000000&limit=10000
```

### AP rows only

```text
https://YOUR_APP_URL/export/bars.csv?secret=YOUR_SECRET&stream_id=B2M_AP&limit=5000
```

### Pivot rows only

```text
https://YOUR_APP_URL/export/bars.csv?secret=YOUR_SECRET&stream_id=B3M_PIVOTS&limit=5000
```

### Full raw events with payloads

```text
https://YOUR_APP_URL/export/raw_events.csv?secret=YOUR_SECRET&include_payload=1&limit=2000
```

## 6) Practical first use

For your workflow, start with this:

```text
/export/bars.csv?secret=YOUR_SECRET&limit=10000
```

Download that file and upload it here.

If the file is too large, narrow it with:
- `stream_id=`
- `symbol=`
- `from_ms=` and `to_ms=`

## 7) Notes

- The module is fail-closed and requires the same query-string secret style as the receiver.
- By default it excludes heavy `payload` columns from normalized tables. Add `include_payload=1` only when you actually want them.
- `raw_events.csv` also exposes a `payload_preview` virtual column by default when payload columns are present.
- The export routes do not change ingest behavior.
- This is intended as the interim read/export path so you can get the data out of DigitalOcean without relying on MCP.
